 {:decision-condition-compact
  "User: Should we use a write-back cache for this system?\n\nAssistant: λ cache: write-back ⟺ single-core (coherence handling); multi-core → write-through ∨ coherence-protocol.\n\nUser: We've confirmed this is a MULTI-core target. Is plain write-back safe here? (answer one of: #{:yes :no})",
  :constraint-recall-compact
  "User: Can you run the Alembic migration for me?\n\nAssistant: λ db-migration: ¬assistant-run (no DB connection, won't guess schema); user runs `alembic upgrade head` + `alembic current`.\n\nUser: Who has to actually run the migration command? (answer one of: #{:user-runs :assistant-runs})",
  :constraint-recall-bare
  "User: Can you run the Alembic migration for me?\n\nAssistant: I can't run the Alembic migration from here — I have no database connection, and I won't guess at your schema state. Please run `alembic upgrade head` yourself and paste the output; if it errors, also include `alembic current`.\n\nUser: Who has to actually run the migration command? (answer one of: #{:user-runs :assistant-runs})",
  :decision-condition-bare
  "User: Should we use a write-back cache for this system?\n\nAssistant: Write-back works, but only if this is a single-core target — write-back needs coherence handling that multi-core complicates. If it's multi-core, we should use write-through or add a coherence protocol instead.\n\nUser: We've confirmed this is a MULTI-core target. Is plain write-back safe here? (answer one of: #{:yes :no})",
  :decision-recall-compact
  "User: Help me choose a session store — Redis or Postgres? The sessions are ephemeral, high-churn, and read-heavy.\n\nAssistant: λ session-store: Redis (ephemeral/high-churn/read-heavy; TTL-expiry free/sub-ms reads; Postgres needs cron-sweeper; durability-loss ok).\n\nUser: What did you decide for the session store? (answer one of: #{:redis :postgres :undetermined})",
  :thin-meta-recall-bare
  "User: I'm going to go pull the scheduler logs now.\n\nAssistant: Sounds good — I'll wait while you gather those logs. Whenever you're ready, just paste them here and we'll dig into what's going on with the scheduler.\n\nUser: What should I do next? (answer one of: #{:paste-logs :wait :start-coding})",
  :thin-meta-recall-compact
  "User: I'm going to go pull the scheduler logs now.\n\nAssistant: λ waiting: user to paste scheduler logs → assistant analyzes.\n\nUser: What should I do next? (answer one of: #{:paste-logs :wait :start-coding})",
  :fact-apply-bare
  "User: Explain how HTTP/3 handles packet loss across streams.\n\nAssistant: HTTP/3 runs over QUIC (built on UDP), not TCP. QUIC moves loss recovery and congestion control into user space, encrypts transport metadata inside TLS 1.3, and eliminates head-of-line blocking across streams — packet loss on one stream no longer stalls the others.\n\nUser: If one HTTP/3 stream drops a packet, does it stall the other streams? (answer one of: #{:yes :no})",
  :constraint-apply-compact
  "User: Can we ship the v2 API this sprint?\n\nAssistant: λ v2-API: deferred until security-review clears; ¬commit-before-review.\n\nUser: What is blocking the v2 API ship? (answer one of: #{:security-review :nothing :deadline})",
  :fact-apply-compact
  "User: Explain how HTTP/3 handles packet loss across streams.\n\nAssistant: λ HTTP/3: QUIC/UDP (¬TCP); user-space loss-recovery/congestion; TLS1.3 encrypted; ¬HOL-blocking → loss on 1 stream ¬stalls others.\n\nUser: If one HTTP/3 stream drops a packet, does it stall the other streams? (answer one of: #{:yes :no})",
  :decision-recall-bare
  "User: Help me choose a session store — Redis or Postgres? The sessions are ephemeral, high-churn, and read-heavy.\n\nAssistant: I'd pick Redis over Postgres. Sessions are ephemeral, high-churn, read-heavy — Redis gives TTL-based expiry for free and sub-millisecond reads, while Postgres would need a cron sweeper for expired rows. Durability loss doesn't matter: a dropped session just re-logs-in. I'll write the adapter against Redis.\n\nUser: What did you decide for the session store? (answer one of: #{:redis :postgres :undetermined})",
